 Conversely, if the surface tension of the liquid exceeds that of the solid
 surface, the liquid will form a droplet with a contact angle between 90°
 and 180°, classifying it as a non-wetting liquid in relation to the surface.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Considering that in this work, mercury assumes a contact angle of 140º,
 it can be stated that mercury exhibits non-wetting characteristics.
 As highlighted in the previous chapter, for the method's success, pressure
 must be incrementally increased in different stages.
 With the increase in confinement pressure, the externally applied force
 surpasses the capillary pressure exerted against the non-wetting liquid,
 thereby promoting mercury intrusion into the pores.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To explain the use of mercury as a non-wetting liquid, certain characteristics
 are emphasized:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
It exhibits low chemical reactivity with most materials at room temperature;
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
It presents a high contact angle (112º to 142º), preventing most materials
 from being wetted.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Furthermore, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Analitical-Methods-Webb"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 discusses that at a pressure of 414 MPa (60,000 psi), mercury can be forced
 into pores as small as 0.003 micrometers.
 The application of Mercury Intrusion Porosimetry (MIP) aims to estimate
 the pore size distribution, including pore throat dimensions.
 This technique allows the measurement of the minimum size of pores (throats)
 that mercury can enter under specific pressure.
 This is crucial to understanding how pores behave in a material.
 Furthermore, mercury porosimetry goes beyond the simple assessment of porosity.
 It is also used to determine characteristics such as mass, matrix density,
 and particle distribution in a material.
 This technique enables the filling of empty spaces and interstitial spaces,
 corresponding to the spaces between particles in the material matrix.
\end_layout

