\begin_layout Subsection
Data Analysis
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With the central objective of analyzing the pore distribution of the Barra
 Velha formation, located in the Santos Basin, this study will employ the
 Washburn Equation as a fundamental tool in classifying pore throat sizes
 into:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Micropores; 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Mesopores; 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Macropores.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Washburn equation relates applied pressure, pore size, and properties
 of the involved fluids, enabling pore diameter calculations.
 The significance of applied pressure and interfacial tension angle (also
 known as contact angle) is pivotal to this relationship.
 In this model, applied pressure and interfacial tension angle are crucial
 as they determine mercury's ability to intrude into pores, thereby ensuring
 accuracy in pore size distribution characterization.
 The applied pressure must be sufficient to overcome capillary resistance,
 while the contact angle adjusts the equation to reflect the specific interactio
n between mercury and the material surface, accurately calculating pore
 radii.
 Interfacial tension, in turn, represents the force acting at the interface
