\begin_layout Section
Porosity Analysis
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As described in subsection 3.2.2, as pressure increases, mercury begins to
 fill the porous space.
 Generally, there is a limit beyond which no further increase in displaced
 volume is observed, even with increased pressure.
 Upon reaching this limit, it is understood that all porous space has been
 filled, and therefore, the displaced volume corresponds to the porous volume
 of the sample.
 Porosity can be estimated as the ratio between the volume of pores and
 the total volume.
 If the sample weight is known, the volume and density of the matrix can
 be calculated by subtracting the porous volume from the total volume.
 The total density is calculated as the ratio of the sample weight to the
 total volume 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
